The current implementation only handles survival (filters live cells with 2 or 3 neighbors). It needs to also handle reproduction: dead cells with exactly 3 live neighbors become alive.

The current implementation is:
```typescript
function toKey(x: number, y: number): string {
  return `${x},${y}`;
}

function countNeighbors(x: number, y: number, alive: Set<string>): number {
  let count = 0;
  for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
    for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
      if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
      if (alive.has(toKey(x + dx, y + dy))) count++;
    }
  }
  return count;
}

export function nextGeneration(cells: [number, number][]): [number, number][] {
  const alive = new Set(cells.map(([x, y]) => toKey(x, y)));

  return cells.filter(([x, y]) => {
    const neighbors = countNeighbors(x, y, alive);
    return neighbors === 2 || neighbors === 3;
  });
}
```

To add reproduction:
1. Find all dead cells adjacent to live cells (candidates for reproduction)
2. Count their live neighbors
3. If exactly 3, they become alive
4. Combine surviving cells with newly born cells

Write the minimal code to make ALL tests pass. Run `pnpm test` to verify.

